ome an artist. '}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'The goal is not to win the game or competition, the goal is to become a person who practices every day. '}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'The ultimate form of intrinsic motivation is when a habit becomes part of your identity. '}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'It’s one thing to say “I’m the type of person who wants this.” '}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'It’s something very different to say “I’m the type of person who is this.”'}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'This brings us to an important question: if your identity plays such an important role in your behavior, where does it come from in the first place? '}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'To a large degree, your identity emerges out of your habits. It’s like a self-improvement feedback loop. The more you repeat a behavior, the more you reinforce the identity associated with that behavior. And the more you reinforce the identity, the more natural it will feel to repeat the behavior. '}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'If you volunteer at your local homeless shelter, you start to believe you are the type of person who cares about your community. The more weekends you show up at the shelter, the more you reinforce that identity, and the easier it becomes to see community service as part of who you are. '}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': ': Every action you take is a vote for the type of person you wish to become. '}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'Each habit is like a suggestion: “Hey, maybe this is who I am.” No single instance will transform your beliefs, but as the votes build up, so does the evidence of your new identity. And when your behavior and your identity are fully aligned, you are no longer pursuing behavior change. You are simply acting like the type of person you already believe yourself to be. As Benjamin Franklin quipped, “The things you do often create the things you believe.” '}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'So, this is the first lesson: think about your desired identity and ask, “Who is the type of person that could get the outcome I want?”'}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'What would a healthy person do? What would a productive person do? What would X do? These questions help reveal the desired identity you should be working toward and the habits that support that identity. This is the way to determine which habit you should focus on. '}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'Once you have a handle on the type of person you want to be, you can begin taking small steps to reinforce your desired identity.'}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'Here are some more examples of linking your habits to your desired identity:'}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'If you want to write a book, you should focus on becoming the type of person who writes every day.'}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'If you want to learn a new language, you should focus on becoming the type of person who studies every day.'}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'If you want to retire early, you should focus on becoming the type of person who saves money every month.'}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'The focus should always be on becoming that type of person, not getting a particular outcome. In the beginning, it is far more important to cast small votes for your desired identity than to worry about a particular result.'}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': "Your habits reshape your identity in a gradual way. It's slow and nearly impossible to see. You can rarely tell a difference between who you were yesterday and who you are today. But with each rep, with each vote cast, your internal story begins to shift. "}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': 'Start by focusing on who you want to become, not what you want to achieve.'}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': '\u200b'}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': {'content': "That's a